<font color="#FF0000">WHAT TO WRITE ?</font><br>
<tt>Mon Dec 15 12:55:42 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook, You have brought up on a number of occasions that your command was hassling you to get in touch with your family.  You sound like you resented your wife constantly contacting others to get you to write home.  Are you saying that you had initially written home and she told you she didn't want to hear the war stories, so you stopped writing all together? Or, was there trouble at home before you even reported to Vietnam? Over.<br><br>
Some of the details of missions that I understand after the fact a number of men wrote home to their family amazes me.  Reason?  I was ORDERED NOT  to take pictures of any patients (they would show the men were still getting hit hard), or write home what I knew was going on (cause that was in direct conflict with the official stance that the war was winding down).  If you go back into the official records at the national archives or the war college you will find very little documentation after 1970 (missing annual reports, after action reports, personel totals...everything).  Its almost as if those of us who were there in 1971 or later didn't exist. The military was shipping home many troops, the return numbers were recorded but the number of new soldiers shipped over to replace those sent home were hidden from the media.<br><br>
What do you write when you can't write the truth?  Basically you lie, or you write about very little, tell them you love them and are looking forward to the day you'll see them again,  but you still send a letter periodically because that lets them know you are still alive.  For as difficult as being in Vietnam was for you, waiting at home and loving someone who was in Vietnam was also difficult for the spouses and parents.  They hurt too!  In Vietnam we were insulated from the protests, we had a purpose, a job that consumed us.  The families had to live with other relatives, and friends attitudes  against the war; the constant fear that you'd get killed or wounded; not being able to really do anything but having to wait. I hope you can understand why they might want to delude themselves and say everything would be OK.  That didn't necessarily mean they didn't care about you, it could be they cared too much and the separation was painful.   Even if they didn't want to hear you say what you had been through when they saw you still at risk, they did want to know you had  survived another day. <br><br>
You obviously still have a lot of pain associated with your first marriage.   There is a lot that has gone unsaid here and it is counter productive at this point to try to affix blame for what has  transpired.  I am glad to see that you have found someone to love who loves you in return, and you have five beautiful daughters.  I hope your x-wife has also found some sense of peace. OVER.
<p><code>--   (Class Lass) </code><p>


